04975nam a22006135i 9780822384663DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223846637 a10.1515/97808223846632doi  a(DE-B1597)554131  a(OCoLC)1229161272  a(OCoLC)1168425337  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPS78b.O38 2003 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a801/.95/0973090452211 aO'Hara, Daniel T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEmpire Burlesque :bThe Fate of Critical Culture in Global America /cDaniel T. O'Hara; Donald E. Pease. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource (386 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Americanists00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: We Welcoming Others, or What's Wrong with the Global Point of View? -- tI. Reading as a Vanishing Act -- t1. Edward W. Said and the Fate of Critical Culture -- t2. Why Foucault No Longer Matters -- t3. Lentricchia's Frankness and the Place of Literature -- tII. Globalizing Literary Studies -- t4. Redesigning the Lessons of Literature -- t5. The Return to Ethics and the Specter of Reading -- t6. Class in a Global Light: The Two Professions -- tIII. Analyzing Global America -- t7. Transference and Abjection: An Analytic Parable -- t8. Ghostwork: An Uncanny Prospect for New Americanists -- t9. Specter of Theory: The Bad Conscience of American Criticism -- tIV. Reading Worlds -- t10. Empire Baroque: Becoming Other in Henry James -- t11. Planet Buyer and the Catmaster: A Critical Future for Transference -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEmpire Burlesque traces the emergence of the contemporary global context within which American critical identity is formed. Daniel T. O'Hara argues that globalization has had a markedly negative impact on American cultural criticism, circumscribing both its material and imaginative potential, reducing much of it to absurdity. By highlighting the spectacle of its own self-parody, O'Hara aims to shock U.S. cultural criticism back into a sense of ethical responsibility.Empire Burlesque presents several interrelated analyses through readings of a range of writers and cultural figures including Henry James, Freud, Said, De Man, Derrida, and Cordwainer Smith (an academic, spy, and classic 1950s and 1960s science fiction writer). It describes the debilitating effects of globalization on the university in general and the field of literary studies in particular, it critiques literary studies' embrace of globalization theory in the name of a blind and vacant modernization, and it meditates on the ways critical reading and writing can facilitate an imaginative alternative to institutionalized practices of modernization. Drawing on Lacanian psychoanalytical theory, it diagnoses contemporary American Studies as typically driven by the mindless abjection and transference of professional identities.A provocative commentary on contemporary cultural criticism, Empire Burlesque will inform debates on the American university across the humanities, particularly among those in literary criticism, cultural studies, and American studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aCriticismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJournalismzUnited States. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aMass media and culturezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aPease, Donald E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-